Here are the specific code snippets from the project that handle the authentication state, the "Loading..." display, and the logout function.

### 1. Auth Store (`src/store/authStore.ts`)
This is the core logic that manages the user session, the profile fetching, and the logout process using Supabase.

```typescript
import { create } from 'zustand';
import { supabase } from '../lib/supabase';
import { useGameStore } from './gameStore';

export const useAuthStore = create((set, get) => ({
  user: null,
  profile: null,
  loading: true,

  // Robust profile fetching with failsafe for production
  refreshProfile: async () => {
    const { user } = get();
    if (!user) return;

    try {
      const { data, error } = await supabase
        .from('profiles')
        .select('*')
        .eq('id', user.id)
        .single();

      if (data) {
        set({ profile: data });
        useGameStore.getState().syncUser({
          id: data.id,
          username: data.username,
          balance: data.balance
        });
      } else if (error && error.code === 'PGRST116') {
        // PGRST116 = Profile missing. Attempt to create it.
        const newProfile = {
          id: user.id,
          username: user.user_metadata?.username || user.email?.split('@')[0] || 'Player',
          balance: 10000.00
        };
        const { data: inserted } = await supabase.from('profiles').insert([newProfile]).select().single();
        if (inserted) {
          set({ profile: inserted });
          useGameStore.getState().syncUser(inserted);
        }
      } else {
        // FALLBACK: If DB fails or network is blocked, use metadata to prevent "Loading..." hang
        const fallback = {
          id: user.id,
          username: user.user_metadata?.username || 'Player',
          balance: 10000.00
        };
        set({ profile: fallback });
        useGameStore.getState().syncUser(fallback);
      }
    } catch (err) {
      console.error('Auth Error:', err);
    }
  },

  // Logout Function: Clears both Supabase session and local storage
  signOut: async () => {
    try {
      await supabase.auth.signOut();
      for (const key in localStorage) {
        if (key.includes('supabase.auth')) localStorage.removeItem(key);
      }
    } finally {
      set({ user: null, profile: null });
      useGameStore.getState().syncUser(null);
    }
  }
}));

// Listener that handles the "Loading..." state transition
supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange(async (event, session) => {
  const store = useAuthStore.getState();
  if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
    store.setUser(session.user);
    await store.refreshProfile();
  } else {
    store.setUser(null);
    store.setProfile(null);
  }
  useAuthStore.setState({ loading: false });
});
```

### 2. Where "Welcome Loading..." is displayed (`src/components/Header.tsx`)
This component renders the top bar. It uses the `profile?.username` and falls back to "Loading..." if the store hasn't populated the profile yet.

```tsx
export default function Header() {
  const { profile, signOut } = useAuthStore();

  // This is where the text you see is generated
  const usernameDisplay = profile?.username || 'Loading...';

  return (
    <header className="bg-red-600 text-white p-4">
      <div className="flex items-center justify-between">
        <div className="flex items-center gap-3">
          <div className="w-10 h-10 rounded-full bg-white/20 flex items-center justify-center font-bold">
            {profile?.username?.substring(0, 2).toUpperCase() || 'GU'}
          </div>
          <div>
            <p className="text-xs text-red-100 opacity-80">Welcome,</p>
            <p className="text-sm font-bold leading-none">{usernameDisplay}</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        {/* Logout Button */}
        <button onClick={() => signOut()} className="p-2 hover:bg-white/10 rounded-full">
           <LogoutIcon />
        </button>
      </div>
    </header>
  );
}
```

### 3. App Initialization (`src/App.tsx`)
The `App` component manages the global `loading` state. If `loading` is true, it prevents the game from rendering.

```tsx
export default function App() {
  const { user, loading, initialize } = useAuthStore();

  useEffect(() => {
    initialize(); // Sets loading: true on start
  }, []);

  if (loading) {
    return (
      <div className="min-h-screen bg-gray-950 flex flex-col items-center justify-center">
        <div className="text-red-600 animate-pulse font-black text-2xl">
          LOADING...
        </div>
      </div>
    );
  }

  // If loading is false but no user, show login page
  if (!user) return <AuthPage />;

  // Otherwise show the main game
  return <MainGameUI />;
}
```

These snippets show exactly how the state moves from **Supabase -> AuthStore -> Header**. The "Loading..." hang usually happens if `refreshProfile` never finishes or doesn't set a fallback.

content.text:
I see exactly what is causing the freeze here. The issue stems from how you are trying to update the Zustand store inside your Supabase auth listener.
At the bottom of your authStore.ts, your onAuthStateChange listener is trying to call store.setUser(session.user) and store.setProfile(null). The problem is that neither setUser nor setProfile actually exist inside your Zustand create block.
Because those functions aren't defined, the listener throws a silent JavaScript TypeError and crashes in the background the moment you refresh the page or try to log out. Since it crashes immediately, it never reaches await store.refreshProfile(). This leaves your user object populated (which lets you into the main app route) but your profile object as null, causing your Header to permanently display "Welcome Loading...". This exact same crash is what intercepts and breaks your logout function.
To fix this, you need to use Zustand's built-in setState method when you want to modify the store from the outside.
Here is the corrected listener code. Just replace the current onAuthStateChange block at the bottom of your authStore.ts with this:
```javascript
supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange(async (event, session) => {
  if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
    // Update state directly using Zustand's setState
    useAuthStore.setState({ user: session.user });

    // Fetch the profile now that the user is set
    await useAuthStore.getState().refreshProfile();
  } else {
    // Clear everything if logged out or anonymous
    useAuthStore.setState({ user: null, profile: null });
  }

  // Resolve the loading state only after the profile fetch finishes (or fails)
  useAuthStore.setState({ loading: false });
});

```
As a secondary detail, your signOut function has a bug waiting to happen. Using a for...in loop on localStorage is risky because it iterates over built-in prototype properties (like length or setItem) alongside your actual keys. When it hits a property that isn't a string, key.includes will throw an error, which could also be contributing to your logout button freezing. Supabase's signOut() method automatically clears its own auth tokens anyway, so manual wiping is usually overkill.
If you really want a scorched-earth cleanup on logout just to be safe, it's better to clear it like this:
```javascript
  signOut: async () => {
    try {
      await supabase.auth.signOut();

      // Safely iterate only over actual storage keys
      Object.keys(localStorage).forEach(key => {
        if (key.includes('supabase.auth')) {
          localStorage.removeItem(key);
        }
      });
    } finally {
      useAuthStore.setState({ user: null, profile: null });
      useGameStore.getState().syncUser(null);
    }
  }

```
Make those two swaps and your refresh sequence will actually finish fetching the profile, and your logout button will stop choking on undefined functions.

