To fix this, you need to use Zustand's built-in setState method when you want to modify the store from the outside.
Here is the corrected listener code. Just replace the current onAuthStateChange block at the bottom of your authStore.ts with this:
```javascript
supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange(async (event, session) => {
  if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
    // Update state directly using Zustand's setState
    useAuthStore.setState({ user: session.user });

    // Fetch the profile now that the user is set
    await useAuthStore.getState().refreshProfile();
  } else {
    // Clear everything if logged out or anonymous
    useAuthStore.setState({ user: null, profile: null });
  }

  // Resolve the loading state only after the profile fetch finishes (or fails)
  useAuthStore.setState({ loading: false });
});

```
As a secondary detail, your signOut function has a bug waiting to happen. Using a for...in loop on localStorage is risky because it iterates over built-in prototype properties (like length or setItem) alongside your actual keys. When it hits a property that isn't a string, key.includes will throw an error, which could also be contributing to your logout button freezing. Supabase's signOut() method automatically clears its own auth tokens anyway, so manual wiping is usually overkill.
If you really want a scorched-earth cleanup on logout just to be safe, it's better to clear it like this:
```javascript
  signOut: async () => {
    try {
      await supabase.auth.signOut();

      // Safely iterate only over actual storage keys
      Object.keys(localStorage).forEach(key => {
        if (key.includes('supabase.auth')) {
          localStorage.removeItem(key);
        }
      });
    } finally {
      useAuthStore.setState({ user: null, profile: null });
      useGameStore.getState().syncUser(null);
    }
  }

```
Make those two swaps and your refresh sequence will actually finish fetching the profile, and your logout button will stop choking on undefined functions.

