content.text:
That console warning is the exact missing puzzle piece we needed. The "Force clearing loading state after 3s" message tells us exactly why the previous fix didn't stick. Your initialize() function is actively fighting with the Supabase auth listener.
Here is what is happening behind the scenes when you refresh the page. The Supabase listener at the bottom of your file fires instantly and tries to set things up. But a split-second later, App.tsx mounts and runs your initialize() function. That function is forcing the app back into a loading state and kicking off a 3-second timer. It manages to set your user session but completely skips the profile fetch. When the timer hits 3 seconds, it gives up, forces the loading screen away, and drops you into the app. Because the profile fetch was bypassed during that mess, your Header has no data and gets permanently stuck on "Welcome Loading...".
To fix this for good, we need to stop them from competing. The cleanest approach is to combine them so there is only one source of truth for your auth state. We will move all the logic into a single initialize function inside your store and get rid of those hacky 3-second timeouts entirely.
Replace your current initialize function inside authStore.ts with this code:
```javascript
  initialize: () => {
    set({ loading: true });

    // 1. Fetch the initial session on load
    supabase.auth.getSession()
      .then(async ({ data: { session } }) => {
        if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
          set({ user: session.user });
          await get().refreshProfile();
        } else {
          set({ user: null, profile: null });
        }
        set({ loading: false });
      })
      .catch((err) => {
        console.error('Session error:', err);
        set({ loading: false });
      });

    // 2. Listen for any future login/logout events
    supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange(async (event, session) => {
      // Ignore the initial event since getSession handles it
      if (event === 'INITIAL_SESSION') return; 

      if (session?.user && !session.user.is_anonymous) {
        set({ user: session.user });
        await get().refreshProfile();
      } else {
        set({ user: null, profile: null });
      }
      set({ loading: false });
    });
  }

```
Once you paste that inside your store, delete the standalone supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange block at the very bottom of the file. Now, when App.tsx calls initialize(), it acts as the sole manager of your auth flow. It grabs the session directly from storage, properly waits for the profile fetch to finish, handles your logouts naturally, and completely eliminates that 3-second timeout crash.

